On Yom HaShoah, President Joseph R. Biden Jr. stands in solidarity with the Jewish people to remember the Holocaust and reflect on its horrors. He honors the memories of the six million Jews and millions of other victims who were systematically murdered by the Nazis. He emphasizes the importance of remembering the Holocaust and sharing its truth with each new generation to prevent such a tragedy from happening again. President Biden shares his personal experience of learning about the Holocaust from his father and taking his own children and grandchildren to visit Dachau. He stresses the need to speak out against anti-Semitism and all forms of hatred. President Biden acknowledges the unique challenges faced by Holocaust survivors and their descendants, calling for justice, dignity, and support for them. He also emphasizes the importance of countering bigotry directed at marginalized communities. President Biden proclaims April 4 through April 11, 2021, as a week of observance of the Days of Remembrance of Victims of the Holocaust. He calls upon the people of the United States to remember and honor the victims and survivors of the Holocaust.